Sure! Here's an example of a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("input.txt");
    std::string wordToSearch = "example";
    std::string line;
    int count = 0;

    if (file.is_open()) {
        while (getline(file, line)) {
            std::stringstream ss(line);
            std::string word;
            while (ss >> word) {
                if (word == wordToSearch) {
                    count++;
                }
            }
        }
        file.close();
        std::cout << "The word '" << wordToSearch << "' occurs " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "Unable to open file." << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we open the file "input.txt" and define the word we want to search for (in this case, "example"). We then read the file line by line and use a stringstream to extract each word from the line. We compare each word with the word we are searching for and increment the count if a match is found. Finally, we print the number of occurrences of the word in the file.
